SIMPLE: sparkle
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sparkle
<hw>Spar"kle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Dim. of
<ets>spark</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A little spark; a
scintillation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As fire is wont to quicken and go⟦br⟧
From a <qex>sparkle</qex> sprungen amiss,⟦br⟧
Till a city brent up is.</q> <rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The shock was sufficiently strong to strike out some
<qex>sparkles</qex> of his fiery temper.</q>
<rj><qau>Prescott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Brilliancy; luster; <as>as, the <ex>sparkle</ex> of
a diamond</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sparkle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sparkle
<hw>Spar"kle</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sparkled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Sparkling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[See
<er>Sparkle</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, Spark of fire.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>To emit sparks; to throw off ignited or incandescent particles; to
shine as if throwing off sparks; to emit flashes of light; to
scintillate; to twinkle; <as>as, the blazing wood <ex>sparkles</ex>; the
stars <ex>sparkle</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A mantelet upon his shoulder hanging⟦br⟧
Bretful of rubies red, as fire <qex>sparkling</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To manifest itself by, or as if by, emitting sparks;
to glisten; to flash.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I see bright honor <qex>sparkle</qex> through your eyes.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To emit little bubbles, as certain kinds of liquors;
to effervesce; <as>as, <ex>sparkling</ex> wine</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To shine; glisten; scintillate; radiate;
coruscate; glitter; twinkle.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sparkle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sparkle
<hw>Spar"kle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To emit in the form or likeness
of sparks.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Did <xex>sparkle</xex> forth great light.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sparkle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Sparkle
<hw>Spar"kle</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[Cf. <er>Sparble</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To disperse.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Landgrave hath <qex>sparkled</qex> his army without any
further enterprise.</q> <rj><qau>State Papers.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To scatter on or over.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Purchas.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sparkler</ent>⟦br⟧
